Package com.shouldis.bitset.parallel

Class Biterator

java.lang.Object
com.shouldis.bitset.parallel.Biterator
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.util.Spliterator<java.lang.Integer>, java.util.Spliterator.OfInt, java.util.Spliterator.OfPrimitive<java.lang.Integer,​java.util.function.IntConsumer,​java.util.Spliterator.OfInt>
Direct Known Subclasses:
DeadBiterator, LiveBiterator, SizedBiterator
public abstract class Biterator
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Spliterator.OfInt
Bit Iterating implementation of Spliterator that is meant to be used in conjunction with BitSets. This class allows for parallel processing on the indices of a BitSet such that those operations will never enter race conditions on the underlying longs within BitSet.words. This behavior can only be guaranteed if the indices returned by the Biterator are manipulated, and not some offset or translation. This bounding of indices to specific threads is necessary because of the non-atomic nature of modifying a long. Using a generic parallel IntStream would cause changes to the underlying long words of a BitSet to be potentially overridden by other threads manipulating nearby bits.
Author:
Aaron Shouldis
See Also:
BitSet, SizedBiterator

  • Field Details

    • THRESHOLD

      protected static final int THRESHOLD
      The minimum threshold of remaining indices for which a Biterator will refuse a call to Spliterator.trySplit(). Equal to the size of 4 long words to ensure splitting is worthwhile, and leaves each process with at least 1 word to process.

    • nextLiveBit

      protected final int nextLiveBit​(long word, int wordIndex)
      Calculates the index of the next live bit within a specified word that is at the specified wordIndex within BitSet.words. This index will represent its bit index in the underlying long array as well as the offset within the integer word.
      Parameters:
      word - the long word to be checked for a live bit.
      wordIndex - the index of the word within BitSet.words.
      Returns:
      the index of the next live bit within the specified word, or end if none are found.
